text:
dear america,
i never agreed to be black. or what youâ€™ve agreed that it is before me. we are told who we are by societiesâ€™ agreements. but my ancestors had no seat at the table, no consent in something that concerned them and their descendants. dealing with the results of agreements we made for ourselves is fair. if you agree to be a doctor, a dj, to a marriage or a friendship â€” there are aspects of life that are obtainable and certain ones that are not based on your agreements. this is natural. donâ€™t like aspects of your life? youâ€™re free to change agreements around your job or break off relationships. 
what isnâ€™t natural; we demand and expect full participation in the predetermined agreements around race without the consent of the people who are affected by them the most. kinda like a #metoo on life itself. life abuse. demanding my participation in this abuse america and its institutions have perpetrated against those of my shade with impunity is the antithesis of liberty. my liberty as a citizen and the liberty of my soul as a conscious being. my acceptance of the agreement is my imprisonment. even the soft bigotry of low expectations is a burden too heavy for my unwilling shoulders. some of you may be amused, others confused, some angered by the sheer notion of what iâ€™m suggesting. black and white alike. understand that i donâ€™t care enough about white privilege to appease it and i donâ€™t care enough about black burden to continue to carry it or fulfill someone elseâ€™s expectations surrounding it. being black should not mean being burdened by a nation or a mind. i didnâ€™t agree to participate in this charade of value. race is an invention. unlike others it has yet to prove its usefulness. but has a purpose for the inventor. itâ€˜s been a weapon to divide would be allies in the truth of human equity. separating us from our common struggles and imprisons our ideas and thoughts about ourselves and others. which allows the status quo to remain. thatâ€™s only good for whoâ€™s currently in power. i wonâ€™t allow my true self to be imprisoned. not by a society or my own mind. self that is beyond race and gender. what we call a soul. iâ€™m writing a book on this. more to come. á‚

text:
do you want to know a secret. . . ? 
you are beautiful as you are, right here, right now.  your body is beautiful as it is, right here, right now.

why am i sharing this â€œsecretâ€ with you?  well, i have seen many, many, many women struggle the night of and day after the victoriaâ€™s secret fashion show - which was on tonight.

before you begin to compare yourself to those beautiful ladies that were strutting down the walkway on your big screen tv, take a pause.  remember that they are a very small minority of what women look like.  majority of the women in this world do not look like that - and that is okay. .

you have your own attributes that make you your special and unique self.  playing the comparison game will only make you feel like shit - and thatâ€™s not a good way to end the weekend or begin a new week.

you are beautiful - just as you are - right here, right now.

you are beautiful ğŸ’œ

prasarita padottasana has many heal benefits? 
prasarita padottasana -(wide-legged standing forward bend), it lengthens the spinal column and stretches the back of the legs and back muscles. this pose helps calm the mind, providing relief from anxiety, stress, back pain, shoulder tension and helps open up the hips. also helping to quiet and sooth the nervous system.

text: trigger warning! details on why i didn't report (my rape) when i was homeless. i was out of the loop and laying low when the #whyididntreport hashtag gained momentum. but it's good that it did and even though i have not wanted to participate in #metoo discussions, i feel i'm at a place now where i can. at least for now. i posted a 10 min video to my mermeia channel which you can access in my bio. if you can stomach the topic and want to check it out, please do. it is a super complicated subject. perpetrators of assault and harrassment do not discriminate against age, gender, or a person's integrity or self worth. it can happen to anyone. and the reasons why people don't report are as different as each individual survivor. #believesurvivors #believewomen #believemen #hurtpeoplehurtpeople #metoo #sexualassault #sexualabuse #sexualharassment #endthecycle #ptsd #ptsdrecovery #survivor @whyididntreport @ronanfarrow

text:
i posted this on fb, posting here too. update on my absence and a look into my heart. hoping to educate and minister. warning, it is a heart full.

my voice has been silenced, ignored, manipulated, rejected, used, abused, bullied, and discarded.
i'm taking a stand to say: enough is enough.

the time has come for me to speak on here. 
itâ€™s not for validation, consolation, forgiveness, approval or revenge, but for the sake of truth. 
please know and hear that i am speaking from a place of being humbled greatly and continuing to be, from being blinded by sin, and from a place of deep, agonizing pain. pain from which has hit me in waves and the waves keep coming. 
it started out with grief in the loss of a person i truly, deeply loved with great strength and heart. all memories, experiences were curated deep. the good and the bad. why? because i loved and i tried to surrender each moment to god, walk as he would have me. to which i failed again and again and again, but i chose to keep walking. it was my joy to walk with him. my saying yes to him the second time (yes second time)  was not taken lightly, it was not nothing. (and t, no, it was not because i was not dating anyone else. how dare you talk as if you know my story.  oh the terrible counsel to which he was given to come to me, just because he desiredâ€¦ more on that later). i had not talked to him for years. enough time for us to grow and mature. he reached out to me so unexpectedly. i was curious though my heart still very cold towards him. we meet up and unexpectedly, my heart thawed. i saw him and remembered all the things, the reasons why i was with him long ago. he felt like home, i thought he was safe. if you knew our story, years ago we dated and were engaged. this wasnâ€™t a person i was going to mess around with. i was going to be honest and put it all the table. and so i did. iâ€™m in it for the long haul. and this wasnâ€™t flippant for me. i reached out to mentors, my family, friends, prayed, and processed together. 
the truth is that he was never safe and still is not safe. he never loved me and is very twisted on what love and care is. he just used and abused me. eight plus years of it. (cont. â¬‡ï¸)

text:
this is me now. 
however dec 3, 2017 was a day i thought i would never live to see.  i made a choice to not only keep my kids safe, but myself. enough was enough. i was granted a gift.
i knew i had so much more life to live. i had to be strong.
i wanted to set an example for my daughter. for all women.
for anyone who didn't believe they were worth more or deserved more.
 i was scared, but i was strong. i was nervous, but i was fierce. i chose me. 
i still check over my shoulder. sometimes i feel uneasy. but i will not hide in fear. i will not allow someone to have control over my life ever again.

#metoo #instawomen #domesticviolence #speakup #healing #onedayatatime #actnow #help #awareness

text: the healing process was and still is difficult...the nightmares, the flash backs, the anxiety while in the car or alone with somebody...it takes time yâ€™all! itâ€™s so important to seek support. in my case i found a therapist i was comfortable with and was able to process it with. not only that i began working with victims and was able to educate students from elementary school up to college on sexual assault awareness. i found it in myself to help others who could be or have been in my situation or similar. i continue to work on me, help others, identify my triggers, and to find forgiveness in my heart and forgive those who have hurt me and others sexually, mentally, and physically. i have become so much stronger and although if i could i would absolutely take back that night and the terror i felt...i am thankful for my life at where i am now...i am thankful for the strong woman i have become, and the things i have learned. this tattoo represents more than just the sexual assault ribbon...it means a lot to me...â€we all carry these things inside that no one else can see. they hold us down like anchors, they drown us out at sea...but i refuse to sink. life's roughest storms prove the strengths of our anchors.â€ â¤ï¸

text:
â€ª"winter is here, blame persephone!" i used to say. recently i noticed it was not her fault.â€¬
-
â€ªpersephone was the beautiful daughter of demeter, the goddess of harvest and fertility, and zeus the king of gods of mount olympus. basically, upsetting persephone's parents was a really bad idea but hades, god of the underworld, never got the memo. he fell "in love" with the sheltered persephone.â€¬
-
â€ªin greek mythology, hades is described as a middle aged man, living in the shadows with the dead.  demeter furiously rejects hades's proposal to marry persephone. so the "heartbroken" god of underworld kidnaps persephone. he takes her to the underworld...into the darkness.â€¬
-
â€ªpoor persephone cries day and night. versions of the tale say persephone stopped eating, only cried, and hades rapes her. â€¬
-
â€ªabove ground, her mother demeter searched for persephone everywhere. she too cries night and day but her sadness has severe immediate implications to her surroundings.â€¬
-
â€ªas the god of harvest and fertility, demeter's sadness affected the world. plants started to die, leaves started to dry and it became cold.â€¬
-
â€ªsome versions of the tale say that eating anything in the underworld meant you had to stay there. persephone eats only one thing. tempted by the ruby color and nagging hunger, she eats only 6 grains of a pomegranate. only six.â€¬
-
her mother locates her and zeus summons them to mount olympus. hades makes the case that persephone ate in the underground...and belongs to him.â€¬ â€ª
-
they come to an agreement. for 6 months out of the year, persephone would be with her mother. during those months, demeter would be happy and the earth would have spring and summer. but the last 6 months, in the absence of persephone, it would be autumn and winter.â€¬ â€ª
-
this myth was created to explain the changing of seasons. i remember my middle school class concluded that winter is persephone's fault. she ate from the forbidden pomegranate after all.â€¬ â€ª
-
but no. winter is here, blame hades. â€¬ â€ª
-
and thank god those pomegranates weren't from kandahar or else..we would have winter all year.â€¬ â€ª
-
second picture is the sculpture from 1622 by â€¬berniniâ€ª called the rape of persephone.
name: Mariam A.

â€ªpersephone was the beautiful daughter of demeter, the goddess of harvest and fertility, and zeus the king of gods of mount olympus. basically, upsetting persephone's parents was a really bad idea but hades, god of the underworld, never got the memo. he fell "in love" with the sheltered persephone.â€¬
-
â€ªin greek mythology, hades is described as a middle aged man, living in the shadows with the dead.  demeter furiously rejects hades's proposal to marry persephone. so the "heartbroken" god of underworld kidnaps persephone. he takes her to the underworld...into the darkness.â€¬
-
â€ªpoor persephone cries day and night. versions of the tale say persephone stopped eating, only cried, and hades rapes her. â€¬
-
â€ªabove ground, her mother demeter searched for persephone everywhere. she too cries night and day but her sadness has severe immediate implications to her surroundings.â€¬
-
â€ªas the god of harvest and fertility, demeter's sadness affected the world. plants started to die, leaves started to dry and it became cold.â€¬
-
â€ªsome versions of the tale say that eating anything in the underworld meant you had to stay there. persephone eats only one thing. tempted by the ruby color and nagging hunger, she eats only 6 grains of a pomegranate. only six.â€¬
-
her mother locates her and zeus summons them to mount olympus. hades makes the case that persephone ate in the underground...and belongs to him.â€¬ â€ª
-
they come to an agreement. for 6 months out of the year, persephone would be with her mother. during those months, demeter would be happy and the earth would have spring and summer. but the last 6 months, in the absence of persephone, it would be autumn and winter.â€¬ â€ª
-
this myth was created to explain the changing of seasons. i remember my middle school class concluded that winter is persephone's fault. she ate from the forbidden pomegranate after all.â€¬ â€ª
-
but no. winter is here, blame hades. â€¬ â€ª
-
and thank god those pomegranates weren't from kandahar or else..we would have winter all year.â€¬ â€ª

sometimes women learn the hard way of what it means to freeze in the face of danger. it's a learned habit, sometimes even when no danger is present. body language can speak a thousand words. there is a difference between consent and vacancy. never assume her silence is consent.
â€” b o d y  l a n g u a g e
Â© sarah doughty
.
think about this. if she's making eyes, it doesn't mean consent. if she's barely dressed, it doesn't mean consent. did it ever occur to you that asking if it's okay is not only sexy, but empowering? if she doesn't say yes, the answer is no.
.
.
you might be wondering why i'm sharing this now. you may wonder why anyone with a story of abuse or assault may wait decades before coming forward â€” if they ever say anything at all. the answer is simple: any time is a good time. the issue is unfortunate. that there's not enough people talking about this and how important it is to not only know the difference, but to stop blaming the victims. start conversations. teach your children what's okay and what is not. just do something.
.
and right now, that's exactly what i'm doing. 'we will not be silenced' is an important anthology of poetry, prose, essays, and even art for everyone â€” survivors, victims, help centers, and even law enforcement. and yes, you. find more information about this book and what you can do to help on my website.
.

text:
i was 16 the first time a man ever put his hands on me. he said he loved me and with a shift in the atmosphere came the palms of his hands to my face. he called me all out my name and told me no man one would ever want me but him. the crazy part is, at 16, i believed him.

at 18 i met another man. he loved me too. he loved me so much that he wrapped his right hand around my neck, squeezing every airway shut. with his right hand planted, his left hand grabbed a water bottle and he dashed water in my face so that with every gasp of air i even attempted to take, water would fill my lungs making it impossible to breathe.

glad to see 21, i met someone new. he was different. he was the first man to ever take me to church. he loved me so much that he told me he wanted me to bare his child. he sold me every dream and i bought all of them. until at 7 months pregnant he pushed me out of car. until i was laying in a hospital bed about to give birth to the only life i had left inside of me and i was hiding bruises and bite marks under my gown.

so many of you ask me, â€œhow did @turningpaiges_ begin?â€ it began when god gave me the courage to not give up on life but to instead start turning the pages in my own life to get to new chapters. better chapters. so why do i love so hard? because i know what itâ€™s like to feel loveless. why do i speak out against injustices? because i know what itâ€™s like to wish that someone would have noticed and spoke up about the injustices done to me. why do i serve? because thatâ€™s how i love god, and love heals. iâ€™m @turningpaiges_ because turning pages in the book of life, being the bible, taught me truth and god made all things brand new for me. why wouldnâ€™t i share that?

text:
made this peice at 4:30 am, after spending time thinking too much, worrying too much. i was thinking about home the whole time, and i couldn't help but make something that i hope to see this winter. i've never been sking and i really haven't felt free in a while until i imagined it. as my brush stroked the canvas in shades of blue and white, i felt myself glide and roll in the snow, cold air brushing my cheeks. i lived it.
i stopped painting when my depression got worse. i couldn't express myself anymore, i couldn't do the things i used to enjoy, i couldn't love the same. i wasn't someone i, or anyone recognised. i don't know why i picked the paint brush again, perhaps nothing was entertaining me anymore, or maybe, just maybe...a new beginning

text:
rena romano was a successful sales rep for 20 years and when she was finally able to talk about her childhood sexual abuse her success strengthened.  this shows how sexual assault can weigh on someone for years after it happens, but also shows how much finally speaking up about it can help survivors.  through hearing other people's stories, hopefully more and more people will gain the courage to speak up and better deal with their sexual assault.  #speakup #endsexualassault #metoo

text:
i recently read an article in which the author posited that in order to be successful, it was better to cultivate a variety of skills that complement each other than it was to master a single skill. he was talking about skills in the workplace, but i believe this line of thinking can be applied to any area of our lives. in this case, i apply it to my active endeavors. i thought i had the perfect combination with my trail running + rock climbing. they are perfect complements to each other for my mountain adventures. so where does martial arts fit into that?
.
this month, i celebrate a year of martial arts, a sport i got into almost accidentally and somewhat reluctantly. while i have enjoyed it, it wasnâ€™t until this past month or so when i made the commitment to getting my black belt and started participating in the extra leadership classes that i have started to love this sport too.
.
the thing that i love about kyuki-do is that it combines the kicks and punches of one discipline with the self-defense and weapons training of others. i started leadership classes on a month where the focus was on grappling and we spent entire sessions throwing each other. but when my 5â€™1â€, 111 lb self tossed a fully grown, larger-than-average man over my shoulder, it came to me as i heard the thud of his body hitting the mats when he landed at my feet. i remember looking at my small hands afterwards thinking, â€œi did that.â€
.
a day or two earlier, i had read a horrifying account of an elite hungarian ultra runner who had been brutally attacked and sexually assaulted while out on a run. like her, the reality is that i mostly train, travel, and adventure on my own and i have to worry about this happening to me too. but where iâ€™ve been conditioned to be polite and subservient and not cause a scene, here i am taught to yell, say no, be intense, defend and hit back because my safety is more important than someoneâ€™s feelings. in a world where evil will always exist, rhetoric wonâ€™t save me. all of my precautions might not be enough. but like @run_kiwi_run, i now have a much better chance at saying, â€œnot today, motherfuckerâ€ and living to run another day.

text:
counting down the last two weeks left of undergrad life. & yes, i am flicking off my cap because the struggles it took to get this far is what led me into my field. this is my mini story of how the health care field chose me and to say that we are not alone in adversity:
i am a first-generation college student from a socioeconomically depressed community. coming from a disadvantaged background, the social barriers and determinants that stood in my way stripped away my childhood and young adulthood because my existence was surrounded by substance, physical and sexual abuse. while my original coping mechanism was to hide them away tucked in the back of my mind, i have come to realize that i did not withstand these experiences for nothing. i was meant to use these experiences as the foundation to understand and help others survive together through our shared experiences. although i have been stripped apart of who i was, i am defining who i am in spite of the tremendous amount of adversity iâ€™ve endured. i like the term endurance to describe the long nights i lay awake in bed crying myself to sleep at night, not being able to look at myself in the mirror, feelings of loneliness and complete inconsolable grief to recognize that through the blurred lenses, i am a survivor. to get through my 5 years of schooling is only a tidbit of the challenges that stood in my way, but i found myself here in public health because i vowed for no little girl to ever have to endure the same hardships that iâ€™ve had too if i can prevent it. however, my kuleana is too all the people of hawaiâ€™i, it just started from being the broken little girl myself. and for those who wear their broken hearts on their sleeves, the scars on their arms, the tears in their eyes, the pain hidden behind a smile or a laugh just know i am with you on this journey and we are all survivors. the next steps now in my career is to embrace adversity, look it in the eyes and give voice to survivors because we are a resilient people.
#survivors #resilience #metoo #thisispublichealth #iampublichealth #sexualviolence #childabuse #fostercare #substanceuse #thisismentalhealth #ptsd #depression #anxiety #ocd #add #si

text:
rising: jonesing (9/14) by nicholas jones, 29 october 2018. -

iâ€™m jonesing for a love-sin,
a ride upon the starlight express,
pain, pride, fire, and dominance,
a chance to lay beneath the stars,
and navigate uncharted territory,
in hopes to find the morning glory,
of waking up right next to you,

but itâ€™s still gonna be how itâ€™s gonna be,
and itâ€™s gonna go the way itâ€™s gonna go, 
so donâ€™t be jonesing for a fix that ainâ€™t never gonna come,
just keep digging your ditch until the day is done,
and when itâ€™s time to say goodbye - pack it all in,
and take it with you when you leave,

he may be jonesing for a dose of you,
but you are not obligated to sustain him,
you are not obligated to abstain from happiness just to please him,
and youâ€™re not lesser than a jester when heâ€™s a clown amidst a carnival,
of stranger-friends and fake happiness,
that beckon to be called - because you are better than them,

and without him ever wearing you down,
heâ€™ll be jonesing all around with nothing left to find,
no tears left to cry - no pain and no shame,
because you donâ€™t need a man to pave your way,
and you donâ€™t need him to take your pain away,

iâ€™m jonesing for a venue - a chance to sound the alarms,
to write love on my arms in the place of broken dreams,
to know what unconditional love really means,
the love of harmony - the jonesing for a dose of self-indulgence,
that being sexy and single and free affords to me,
the softness of my skin and the strength within my bones,

sincerely,
mr. jones. -

text:
rising: dust (10/14) by nicholas jones, 10 november 2018. -

when the evasion of trust,
becomes all too real,
just know that you are more,
than dust in the field,
where memory plays tricks,
with your peace of mind,
and if you believe in yourself,
you will win each time,

when your heart is weak,
just close your eyes,
and imagine this,
being prosperous,
and knowing that half the fight,
of being courageous is,
putting yourself back on your feet,
and rising out of your bed,
each and every morning,

be strong - youâ€™ve got this,
and you know all of the hands,
youâ€™ve been dealt before,
so you can do anything,
if you focus more,
of your precious time,
towards persisting the will,
of the dust to rise,
because the skies are clear,
for you - my dear,

love him,
but let him go,
look to the skies,
and like the fury,
of a saint in a rise,
clear the dust,
from both sides,
of your broken wings,
and learn to fly again,
youâ€™ve got this. -

text:
rising: next to never (11/14) by nicholas jones, 18 september 2018. -

i see the roots of destruction,
and the darkest of clouds,
in the most dangerous weather,
before the brightest suns,
come back around again,
to change my mind,
and i see people changing,
next to never - next to never,

i see the burdens hate can bring,
and it just makes me want to sing,
a song for those who fear the tides,
of love in its most purest form,
so i write songs inside my head,
to face the existential dread,
words of praise for harder days,
but still - people change,
next to never - next to never,

i see the faces of those i once knew,
and i feel proud of how we all grew,
from the shells in which we resided,
now that the hurt has all subsided,
iâ€™m proud of them in spite of pain,
you have to lose to seek to gain,
rain will fall and the sun will rise,
and then one day - we all will die,
but the memories will survive,
next to never - next to never,

i saw jim in a cafe the other day,
and we looked in each otherâ€™s eyes,
just so long enough to recognize,
the strands of the purple dreams,
the haze of half a thousand years,
that we left behind - and in all of,
the regret of having left the house,
we parted ways having spoken,
next to never - next to never,

i texted him and told him that i was,
spending my time talking to jesus,
and repenting of my sins thinking,
that somehow it could save him,
and me - from all the sadness that,
surrounded us back then and now,
and maybe we could talk somehow,
next to never - next to never,

and now iâ€™m here growing older,
with each passing day - bolder,
than the one that came before,
and i look back on all those days,
that have passed and still i say,
though i may see you next to never,
i will remember you - always,
i will remember you - always. -

text:
rising: on my way (12/14) by nicholas jones, 31 october 2018. -

for the longest time - i swore that i was falling,
and i didnâ€™t know it then - but i was so blind,
too blind to see that he wasnâ€™t right for me,
so i burned the bridge that i spent so much time building,
to forge a new path - and iâ€™m never looking back,
or at least - thatâ€™s exactly what iâ€™m telling myself today,
and iâ€™ll try my best not to fall back into my old temptations,
of saving someone else too far away from saving,
or blaming someone else for my own misbehaving,
and he wonâ€™t stop me - because iâ€™m on my way,
to a better place - to brighter days - so look out now - â€˜cause iâ€™m on my way. -

text:
rising: heal me (13/14) by nicholas jones, 01 october 2018. -

put your hands on my body parts - and help me mend this broken heart,
because i need your guidance more than i ever needed what came before,
and i never want to turn away from you - beautiful eyes bursting with truth,
real recognizes real the way that i can recognize you from miles away,
a star was born in the midnight sky the night that i made love to you,
because you bring me to my knees in the form of a praise,
worshipping the promise of better days,
because i know that i can stand beside you,
and everything will be okay - so thank you,
and if you ever need someone - to hold you up against darkened suns,
iâ€™m here - and i will heal you the way that you heal me,
rising and rising and rising and rising - eternally.

text:
rising: ashes to ashes (14/14) by nicholas jones, 02 november 2018.

i miss talking to you sometimes - because you had such a way,
of making things make sense - and paying recompense,
for sins that we committed on another - but never each other,
just two angry kids sitting on curbs outside of bars,
talking about mariah carey and vintage cars,
flipping cigarettes into gutters and watching them sink,
and then so suddenly - we can blink,
and weâ€™re gone forever,

forever can seem so futile in the eyes of cynicism,
you told me that my eyes were prisms,
shooting rays and solar flares from beams,
that captured all of your hopes and dreams,
in human form,

i was afraid of thunderstorms so youâ€™d hold me through the night,
but now i sleep with a light on because i know,
that youâ€™re not coming back this time,
so i close my eyes and hope my mind can take,
me back to a place where i know we both belong,
listening to your favorite song - and watching you laugh,
as i tried so desperately to harmonize,
but then iâ€™d give up frustrated and just hum along the rest of the way,
singing on a sunday always made for better days to follow,
but now youâ€™re gone and the heart is only hollow,
as hollow as the fire of the soul,

so even today when iâ€™m sitting on the pier,
the sweet nothings that you whispered in my ear,
after all this time - are still all that i can hear,
angel grows and your favorite show still plays on a loop,
because it became my favorite too - and i miss you,
in the way that a friend misses his best friend,
because maybe thatâ€™s what we should have been,
the whole time that we were together,
time has a way of mending minds,

i miss you so much - and though my words may turn to dust,
i will not interfere - but iâ€™ll open another beer,
and sip it lightly hoping one day you will hear,
the words that fall to this paper as i write them here,
this is how we move forward - this is how to disappear,
ashes to ashes - time passes - and we will carry on,
rising like ashes in a windstorm.

text: in 2006, tarana burke was consumed by a desire to do something about the sexual violence she saw in her community. she took out a piece of paper, wrote â€œme tooâ€ across the top and laid out an action plan for a movement centered on the power of empathy between survivors. more than a decade later, she reflects on what has since become a global movement â€” and makes a powerful call to dismantle the power and privilege that are building blocks of sexual violence. â€œwe owe future generations nothing less than a world free of sexual violence,â€ she says. â€œi believe we can build that world.â€ #ted #tedx #california #metoo #inspiration #inspirationalquotes

text:
rising: breathe, pt. 1 (4/14) by nicholas jones, 12 september 2018. -

all alone in my room at night - a light still shines as i sit to write,
in a moment of intense romantic reflection,
some words for the boys whom iâ€™ve loved before,
but for one reason or another - i am with no more,
itâ€™s time to breathe - itâ€™s time to set you free,

dear nolan,
iâ€™ve thought about you quite a bit over the last six years,
and to this day - i can remember every conversation we ever had,
from day one - and i always told myself that one day weâ€™d be together,
because youâ€™re everything iâ€™ve always known iâ€™ve always wanted,
and i canâ€™t wait to see you again - whenever you decide to let your heart,
bring you on your way back home to me - iâ€™m always down,

dear timothy,
we loved each other so much - more than either of us could understand,
and we tried so hard to make things work,
but sometimes things happens for reasons that at the time,
may seem unclear - and when i think of all the fallen tears,
between the two of us - thatâ€™s when i miss you most,
because the words we used the night i left you,
still ring in my ears after all these years gone by,
and through the passing of time - iâ€™ll pray that the day will come when we find,
peace among the broken pieces - the shards of glass that pervaded our past,
because we both deserve better - and i hope we find it - i hope you find it,

dear john paul,
you taught me to embrace my artistic side,
to be unapologetic in word and form,
to embrace the most beautiful parts of myself,
that i was afraid the world might hate me for,
you taught me not to be ashamed of my impulses,
but i never felt safe in the distance - and it let me down a path of fear,
that i allowed to motivate each decision i made,
and iâ€™m sorry that the price we paid is separate ways,
but iâ€™m always here for you - whenever you should need a friend... continued in pt. 2 -

as i have recently mentioned, iâ€™m slowly reevaluating how i use social media. one thing that i would like to change about this instagram is that i would like to â€œblogâ€ more about my writing process and what iâ€™m reading. i recently read peluda by @melissalozadaoliva and what i loved about this book is that melissa has true, raw talent that she uses to share her personal story of being a latina and a child of parents who immigrated to the us. through this poetry book melissa writes conceptually around her experience with thick body hair and how that has effected her views of not only femininity but specifically what it means to be a latina woman who is adopting multiple cultures into her identity, being pulled in several directions. as a white woman myself, this book was a great mirror to hold to my own experiences and assumptions. melissa writes with rich narratives and often she is poignant and humorous. please check her out if youâ€™re looking for excellent girl power poetry. â™¥ï¸ -

text:
rising: breathe, pt. 2 (4/14) by nicholas jones, 12 september 2018. -

dear connor,
i miss your smile - the way that you lit up the room,
in all honesty - one of my biggest regrets in life was letting you walk away,
and not saying i loved you too - because i did,
i just wasnâ€™t ready - but i was - because you were everything,
i always knew i always needed - and for the life of me,
i canâ€™t remember why i chose not to see it through,
but i always loved you - and i always will,
and iâ€™m more sorry that i could never show you my true feelings,

dear trenton,
looking back - i now can see that we were just kids then - and iâ€™d like to think that one day,
we could be friends again - but i get that it may take a while - and if we do come around again,
iâ€™ll greet you with a smile - wish you well and be on my way,
and with so many more things left to say - i will carry them to my grave,

and itâ€™s probably for the best that certain things are left unsent,
like all of the times that i was alone with each of you - precious moments spent,
i absorbed each and every second and every smile and every secret,
and i will carry them with me forever - and i hope that you still carry me with you too. -

text:
rising: cosmic connection (5/14) by nicholas jones, 29 december 2017. -

laying next to you feels like mixing moonbeams and daydreams,

like a stream of consciousness unbothered by anything and everything,

beyond your bedroom door - big and blue - the world keeps moving,

but weâ€™re standing still and almost simultaneously you feel me and fill me completely,

and all i really know right now is how much i love laying next to you,

you see right through me the same way that a widow looks through a window,

longing for something that seemed like just a taste,

when compared to what comes next - and i will miss your embrace every time that youâ€™re away,

iâ€™ll think of you each and every day without rest,

you are the calm and the tempest and like a cosmic connection - you line and align,

all of my fears with your lips to gods ears,

and then they desolate like pearls of oceanic salt drifting away one grain at a time,

a night-time walk on the beach beneath the blackest sky,

you are the limits of a limitless abyss across years of darkness - you are the stars - you are the light,

you are the cosmic bliss in blackened skies and the want inside the need to know.

b + d. -

how do you reconnect with yourself, your dreams and your hopes?  i reconnect when i visit the ocean (as i did the week of thanksgiving). i feel so aligned when i am near â€œmy waterâ€. i also connect by journaling and exploring what it is that i am really wanting.  i then use my planner to figure out how to put together the steps towards making it happen. 
i find co-regulating with those who support me in working towards making my hopes and dreams a reality to be essential and beneficial.  they are so uplifting for me to spend time with.

make a list of ways you can reconnect with yourself, your hope, and your dreams.  then break it down into smaller steps that you can work on until you make it all your reality.  it is possible! ğŸ’œ

mike argentoÂ |margento@ydr.comÂ |Â 8:31 am est january 10, 2018 ï¿¼Â ï¿¼Â ï¿¼Â ï¿¼ ï¿¼

as the #metoo campaign continues to grow, well-known women in the york community join their voices and share their stories.

jason plotkin, york daily record

the other day, just as theÂ me tooÂ movement was enjoying a deserved day in the spotlight afterÂ the golden globe awards, i got an email from a reader who raised a pretty good question. 
he had watched as just about every otherÂ sentientÂ human with a y chromosome had been pilloried and shamed and stripped of theirÂ livelihoodsÂ for being, well, pigs and doing things that civilized human beings should not have to be told not to do,Â and he wondered about another bearer of the wild-hair gene who had apparently escaped nearly unscathed from the consequences of his deplorable actions. ï¿¼

other guys accused of acting terribly toward women lost their gigs. this guy gets a trophy.

the reader was wondering why pittsburgh steelers quarterback ben roethlisberger has not faced the same kind of consequences as the likes of harvey weinstein, kevin spacey, matt lauer, al franken, charlie rose and louis c.k. 
and i thought, #metoo. 
more:Â sexual harassment is not just a hollywood problem (column)

as you may recall, roethlisberger, poised to make another run at the super bowl as the steelers open post-season play sunday, had beenÂ accused of sexual assault by two women, one in 2009 and the other in 2010. 
the woman who accused him in 2009 filed a civil suit, which was later settled out of court. the other accuser, who told police that roethlisberger had raped her in a bathroom stallÂ atÂ a georgia bar, an accusation supported by statements three of her friends gave police, asked that the case not be prosecuted, concerned that a trial would be "a very intrusive personal experience." the district attorney declined to file charges and announced as much. 
still, the nfl suspended roethlisberger for six games, later reduced to four. he went on to lead the steelers to the super bowl that year,Â losing to the green bay packers.

text:
if being raped wasn't traumatic enough in itself, what's even worse is what people sometimes say to victims of rape. here, vanessa, a survivor herself, relays some of the actual things that people have said to her... and what it does to you.

according to @sophiabush "asking what someone was wearing when they were assaulted is like asking someone what outfit they had on when they were robbed. it doesn't matter. it's a violation that was done to them, not because of them." it's #notokay to victim blame. 
it's #notokay to show no sensitivity to victims. your words have power. .

dastu was 14 years old when her uncle started molesting her dastu was raised by a single mother her father abandoned them when she was a baby dastus mum use to go to work early in the morning she use to leave her daughter with her younger brother to look after her while she goes to works all day he use to take & bring her back from school dastu got very sick one day her uncle calls his sister saying meet us at the hospital the doctor says she had a miscarriage and she will need a surgery dastus mum over hears her brother telling the doctor am her husband and do everything necessary also to not let anyone else know our marriage is still a secret dastus mum being in denial couldn't believe what she heard the moment her brother saw his sister he ran away dastu recovered and slowly got back to being to her old self but somehow both dastu and her mother weren't the same after that incident

text: so this girl turned 29 years young last week! time sure does fly but that's okay because this is my year! i have been through a lifetime of pain, some of which some people may never experience. i have had my ups and downs. battled and still battling depression and anxiety each day. i've made plenty of mistakes along the way, i'm not perfect. at one point i played victim and felt sorry for myself but then i realized that all of my experiences and mistakes made me stronger. thankfully, i have a supportive and loving husband who turned my life around the moment i met him. we too have had our moments and worked through them making our marriage even stronger. so when ever you're feeling like your at your all time low think to yourself what can i learn from this and make sure to tell yourself each day that you are strong and you can handle anything thrown at you! #innerstrength #innerpeace #forgiveness #forgiveyourself #depressionawareness #anxietyawareness #bestrong #metoo #metoomovement #strongerthanhate #strongerthanever #thisisme #cheersto29 #thankfulforlife #veganlife #veganlifestyle #birthdaybabe #cheerstoanotheryear #marriage #lovemyhusband

text_retweet:
@regrann from @warif_ng: day 8 | december 02 
sexual consent is an agreement to participate in sexual activity between two adults (over the legal age of 18). it is a vital concept that needs to be understood when it comes to intimate relations between men and women as it must be freely given, reversible, informed, enthusiastic and specific. when there is no consent, it is sexual violation or rape.

if you are forced to have sex against your will, if you say no, asleep, unconscious, under the influence of alcohol or a controlled drug or substance - you cannot give your consent and you have been sexually assaulted.

no means no! hear word! .

text:
reminder: itâ€™s ok to not be ok. in 2011 a news segment aired, reporting on the 60 year sentence that my attacker received after brutally raping and beating me. the news anchor described me during the trial: â€œ20 years of covering court trials and i donâ€™t think iâ€™ve ever seen a rape victim this calm, this poised, this strong. was able to look her rapist in the eye and said you did this. now youâ€™re going to pay.â€ the title of the news segment: â€œrape victim refuses to be brokenâ€
â€¢
following the trial i felt that my life had to mirror this public persona. the truth: i was broken, and silently struggling in my private life with shame and guilt from my assault. was it my fault for allowing this stranger into my car? was it my fault for drinking that night?
â€¢
additionally, making it to trial was a two year court process, in which my attacker was able to continue (or postpone) our trial eight times. that meant 8 times i had to meet with my attorney, listen to taped statements, go over depositions, and practice cross-examination. that meant 8 times i had to relive every graphic detail of that night, over and over and over again.
â€¢
when i wasnâ€™t dealing with trial or trying to put on a facade of being â€œperfectâ€, i was suffering in silence. i thought that to reveal my emotions and my mess would equate weakness. so i kept it to myself and buried it far below the surface, then relied on alcohol to completely numb and disassociate from the pain. the news anchorsâ€™ words couldnâ€™t be more spot on: i refused to be broken.
â€¢
but i soon found that when you bury and suppress your trauma, that trauma eventually finds a way to speak out loud in your life. for me, it was eating disorders, suicidality, mental health issues, addiction, & violence.
â€¢
when i changed my perspective:
that it was ok to not be strong,
that it was ok to admit that i was weak,
that it was ok to ask for support,
that is was ok to meet my pain with empathy and acceptance...
thatâ€™s when i realized that my brokenness made me better, not necessarily â€œstronger.â€
â€¢
this message is for anyone running from your raw, fucked up, painful mess. stop running, stand in it, own it, welcome it...& itâ€™ll make you better ğŸ’›

text:
i was floored to find such accurate & universally resonating description of harassment on the 6th page of this book itself. i urge everyone to read:
ğŸ‚ğŸ
"why couldn't i not just tell this man to leaveÂ  me alone? i didn't have these thoughts until later, and i don't mean an hour later. i mean twenty years later. at 18, i had no proper understanding of the ways that constituted encroachment. i had a feeling for them, an intution, a sense of repugnance for some situations & some people, but i did not know i had a right not to like, not to have to put up with anybody & everybody coming near. best i could manage was to hope the person concerned would hurry up, say whatever they wanted to say & go away, or else to go away myself, politetly & quickly, the very moment i could."
.ğŸğŸ‚
most of us have never been taught how to react when faced with physical/verbal assualt. instead since childhood we've been groomed to be polite & obedient, especially to those older. and even if sometimes we do tell what happened, we are expected to not to mention it again to others & "just forget it". all this leads to us feeling shame rather than those who should be ashamed. this is why the next time, we don't speak up and then years later when we do find the courage, we are questioned,"why now?"
.â˜˜ï¸
so, i urge everyone to talk about it and to listen, but most of all i urge parents or would-be parents to talk to their kids - at age 5, 10, 13, 17. please don't think they are too young to get it. you won't be protecting their innocence but protecting those who might try to take it away. this talk is the most difficult but it is also the most important. this generation has a duty to stop #metoo & start #neverme. please pass this message along to as many people as you can.ğŸŒ»
.
also, i'm beginning to see why this book won the man booker prize this year. can't wait to read it further & do a full review.â˜˜ï¸
.
.
.

text:
despite many stringent laws and awareness movements such as #metoo, it seems that women are not completely safe yet. in a shameful incident, two youths made an attempt to rape a girl in front of her beau.
according to the report published in the hans india, this incident took place near balaram krishna puram, krishna district. before making an attempt to rape the girl, they tied her beau to a tree. as per the details of the case, the youths followed the lovers who on the bike. when the couple reached subabul farm, the youths tried to rape the girl. however, when passerby rushed to the spot, the youths managed to escape.

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

jon sharman

text:
such gratitude and excitement i feel, to have received my copy of she shoots film issue 3: metamorphosis, 
sent all the way from australia!!
a huge congrats to the @sheshootsfilm team for all their hard work in creating such a gorgeous and successful print, and to all fellow female photographers for contributing their powerful gaze & voice and making this publication what it is. 
i am very much humbled and honored to have had @brokenfreeproject be a part of it. âœ¨

text:
im 7 years old, standing in the waves. 8, 9, 10 foot waves. they keep rolling in. each one, bigger, stronger, meaner than the one before. 
trying to keep my balance. 
they keep hitting me, over, and over, and over again. it's so cold! i can't see the sun. it's dark. im so alone!

finally i get knocked down. but i get back up. then get knocked down. then up again. then down again. im shivering, not just from the cold water, but from the pain. 
each time being cut, and bruised by the coral, and rocks. i'm trying to stand up, i'm trying to hold my breath!

im bleeding, i'm bruised. it's hurts. but i keep getting up. 
each wave, i just stay there. they get bigger, and bigger. they just don't stop. years go on. 
i'm not a young girl anymore. 
but the waves keep coming. 
i learn how to jump over the waves. dive into them. 
then one day, they stop! the storm is gone. 
the ocean is calm. just a ripple here and there. birds chirping. the water turns warm. the sun is shining. not a cloud in the sky. 
it's unsettling, but calm. 
the cuts have turned into scars. the bruises are gone. 
but i still feel the pain. it's hurts inside of me now. the pain is deep. 
what do i do now. all i've known is pain. 
i need to leave this beach. i need to turn around and walk away from here. 
why have i stayed here so long?! i can turn around and walk away. 
that's what i'll do. no looking back. 
the storm is gone. -crg

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
beauty has always been associated with sickness, not with health. the most priceless tulip bulbs in the 1637 tulipmania were infected with a virus that rendered the petals variegated and multicolored. most fashion models until recently sported bodies that can charitably be described only as anorectic or emaciated.

but recent developments have plunged the pathologizing of pulchritude into a nadir. today, the very complimenting of beauty has been pathologized and criminalized. women the world over are on a crusade to outlaw beauty and the discourse that it ineluctably engendered for millennia.

nowadays, women protest indignantly when told that they are attractive. incredibly and inanely, they label "abuse" even merely verbal expressions of admiration: they feel that their boundaries are breached and their trust betrayed. women feel objectified and dehumanized, as though their beauty were an alien and irrelevant aspect of their being, somewhat awkward and shameful.

women claim vociferously that to mark their beauty and sex appeal is to ignore their other offerings and to treat them as inferior. can't one make the same argument about any other human trait? should a public intellectual rail against being singled out for her intellect, a mother for her compassion, an athlete for her physique, and an entrepreneur for her vision and daring? all these are innate, mostly inherited properties, cultivated through the years - exactly like beauty and allure.

women are recklessly undermining the very foundations of inter-gender communication, conflating aggression with assertiveness, abrasiveness with boundary setting, and narcissism with self-confidence. we are going to pay a horrible price for this sick dynamic: pathologizing the beautiful dance between men and women, pathologizing beauty itself.

#beauty #health #women #men #metoo #sexual #harassment #sickness #compliment #samvaknin #gender

text:
since last week you might have seen pictures and videos from the 'let's talk about yest' demonstration in copenhagen. in aarhus (and odense and aalborg) there were demos for consent-based rape legislation too. the copenhageners and the so called national press don't care to mention us, they think they are bigger and better than the rest of us. i don't blame them, due to the national media rarely getting their asses out of the capital, they don't know a thing about what's happening outside their  own bubble.
these are pictures from aarhus. the event was large, noicy and powerful. so many voices of survivors and supporters coming together! thinking about it makes me so proud and so humbled to have been part of giving voice to these people. for a moment we were one, and it was strong, beautiful and empowering.

#letstalkaboutyes #ibelieveher #believeher #metoo #consentculture #consent #justconsent #samtykkebaseretlovgivningnu #mitaarhus #herstoryourstory #samtykkeersexet #samtykkelov #ikkeenmere

@everydaysexismprojectdanmark @amnestydanmark @miklpisofficial @jasminidriss

p. s. credits to the local press for being there @tv2ostjylland â¤ï¸ #notallpress

text:
when women come together, magic happens.. .
.
i was surely in my element and fortunate to be in the company of africa's most inspiring and powerful women at the @motsepefoundation sdg5 breakfast. some, i'm fortunate enough to have as my mentors. .
we were inspired by keynotes, panel discussions and the presence of thought leaders such as un deputy secretary general, amina mohammed, graca machel, thuli madonsela, and our amazing wef family,  rapelang rabana, naadiya moosajie among others.
.
.
thank you dr precious motsepe and the motsepe foundation for hosting this beautiful event. i look forward to working together to accelerate progress on sdg5 by 2030 and onwards. .
.
"freedom cannot be achieved unless women have been emancipated from all forms of oppression". (nelson mandela)

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

text:
in part four of this seven part series, we ask no nation for women author @priyankadubeypictures to:

tell us about your childhood experiences... a book that is both shocking and pertinent... in no nation for women, priyanka dubey travels through large swathes of india, over a period of six years, to uncover the accounts of disenfranchised women who are caught in the grip of patriarchy. 
equally, she asks if after the globally-reported december 2012 gang-rape of nirbhaya in new delhi, indiaâ€™s gender narrative has shiftedâ€”and if it hasnâ€™t, what needs to be done to make this a nation worthy of its girls.

or people with disabilities, who are seven times more likely to be sexually abused. .
itâ€™s about the 60 percent of black girls like me who will be experiencing sexual violence before they turn 18, and the thousands and thousands of low-wage workers who are being sexually harassed right now on jobs that they canâ€™t afford to quit."

text:
the fact that you are still here gives you an advantage. my prayer is that we should not look back. let us look straight ahead.

our experiences, our life lessons derived from our mistakes, defeats and setbacks, must act as springboards to make us start over again. 
what we should consider as a fact is that life changes. you may not have the same life as before, but you can still enjoy your life!" let us learn to accept our mistakes, say sorry where necessary and even say thank you to whoever it may concern. 
at the end of the day, we should be able to look back and appreciate the roles we play as individuals based on the teamwork spirit.

text:
kekerasan seksual di transportasi dan ruang publik masih banyak terjadi. 
menurut catatan tahunan komnas perempuan di tahun 2017, dari 350.000 kasus kekerasan terhadap perempuan yang tercatat, 20% diantaranya terjadi di ruang publik.
.
korban masih saja disalahkan, aparat hukum pun melakukan viktimisasi sementara pelaku bebas berkeliaran. belum adanya aturan khusus tentang kekerasan seksual membuat pencegahan dan penanganan kekerasan seksual terhambat.
.
namun begitu sudah ada ruu penghapusan kekerasan seksual yang direncanakan menjadi payung hukum masih belum disahkan hingga kini.
.
yuk kita kumpul bersama untuk mendorong pengesahannya! sampai bertemu di sana!
.
#gerakbersama #16haktp #sahkanruupks #metoo #hearmetoo

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies. 
they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.
